I’m resistant to write because it verifies reality. The permanence of this defies my logic.

Stephen was the ultimate role model for me: a consistent expression of 
great human, 
great artist, 
great father,
great husband, 
great giver, 
great professional, 
great thinker.

He was the first dancer I met who cared as much about intellectual & self-development and his contribution to the world as his dedication to mastering a craft.

He was a living encyclopedia of so many movement languages. I was enamored in rehearsals when choreographers could throw him into any section. Between his breadth of training, his attitude towards honoring culture and the body mechanics of a genre, AND his ingenuity, he was a trustworthy vessel for countless styles and the humblest creative genius on the project. These qualities made him a glue across generations & a bridge between disparate commercial and street worlds.

I’ve never met someone who adored their wife & children so much, from the moment he told me about Al in the Millennium parking lot til seeing them beaming hand-in-hand a few months ago. He was made of real love, real joy, real kindness.

In grief & the poignance of his relationship to movement, I’m reminded of the hermetic Law of Rhythm: 

“The measure of the swing to the right is the measure of the swing to the left. Rhythm compensates.” If this is true, I acknowledge that the depth of his love meant he had access to an equal depth of pain, something so few of us witnessed and discerned.

This man changed our lives individually, changed our community, changed the industry, improved the world. I’m certain he could not fathom the range of his impact. I’ll forever wish he saw the global outpouring of affection for him.

I’m so lucky to be one of the 100,000s he gave full attention and presence to in conversation, not because I was anyone special, but because he cared about every human in front of him in this way. He deserves every good thing.

Al, we love you so much. So much. You know our community is available 24/7 for you and the kids. We’re ready to show up now, tomorrow and forever. Stephen’s legacy is special, and your lives are sacred in this world. #riptwitch

Will the word "woman" ever fit for me? No. Not going to pretend it will. Not going to pretend it ever has. I've literally never understood what it means to be (or not be) a "woman" because there are infinite depictions around the world and across time, cultures, and peoples.

While #InternationalWomensDay isn't something I resonate with personally, it does motivate me to shout-out all the women in the world who are making it happen every day.. making magic out of ashes and scraps, changing lives and systems and countries, contributing revolutionary innovations across sectors (even though you don't get the proper credit or compensation or positionality). Even as women continue to fight for basic rights and equity, they show up and accomplish the extraordinary.

Today, I celebrate the infinite faces and expressions that womanhood can take, whether you shave your armpits or not, work in a skyscraper or stay at home on a farm, are trans or cis or something else, love nature or anime or coding or knitting or skydiving or pin collecting.

Women - I hope to help create a world where you can safely be ALL you are... you're wonderful.

And to the world: stop being assholes to women. Pay them their worth. Respect their bodies. It's not that hard. <3

In honor of discussing body image and modification on this week’s episode of #DearHollywood, I present to you my reclamation of beautiful, natural body hair! (I thought I’d never be able to deconstruct this one.) The only narrative I heard growing up on set and in society was that hair on female bodies was unsightly, disgusting, and embarrassing. I shaved, lasered, waxed, tweezed.. instead of it being an empowered choice and personal preference, every hair had to be eliminated or else my “womanhood” and desirability were at stake!! (Lolololol.) I’d fully internalized these beliefs and found it horrifying to see anyone who wasn’t a ~straightcisman~ embracing their natural body hair. How dare we?! Well. Thankfully, we made it out of the cage!! And I must say, my fuzzy legs are my fave.

For me, feeling good and authentic and confident nowadays might mean letting my body hair grow for a few weeks, a few years, shaving occasionally, shaving never, manicuring some places, waxing everywhere (ok prob not), who knows?! Gratefully, it’s no longer from a place of fear and judgment. I finally understand that body hair is sexy on everyone, if that’s what feels true and good to you! 😍🥰 Conveniently, the people I find most attractive inside and out usually land somewhere similar, so yayyy… 🥳 If you hate it, we don’t have to date. I was on the verge of giving into the all-too-familiar heaviness and tightness in my chest + mental overwhelm that comes with GAD (generalized anxiety disorder). But, I still had commitments to family, work, and car issues the same night.
I remembered what @coachalyssachang shared in our @MovementGenius class, and it saved the day:

1) Assess *which kind* of stress response you’re in: fight, flight, freeze, or fawn.

2) Use tools for *that specific* state, because certain techniques may be helpful for one, but unhelpful for others (i.e. sitting still to meditate while your body is in “fight mode” and needs to expel energy may not help you move toward a sense of safety). I lowered the lights and closed the door to reduce environmental stimulation. Then, I placed pressure on my chest and relaxed my tongue and jaw.

3) Since catastrophic thinking can be a self-fulfilling prophecy for me, I remembered that our bodies really can shift in a short period, and our near-spiral doesn’t have to ruin the whole day. 

Sometimes Life feels so taut, and I wonder if I’ll be able to handle it with the strength and persistence and selflessness I see my family, friends, and other people have while managing so much. But, I know that moving through this moment mindfully will help build resilience.
If you’re feeling frayed, sending extra love. One moment at a time. 💜
